    "body": "> @benjthayer we need your input to optimize these banners (besides the backup seed phrase). Currently we get a banner as soon an event triggers which might mean that for example if we get disconnected and connected 2 times in a second, we will show 4 banners in this little time which is not very optimal ux and performance wise. How could we improve/simplify the current banners behavior? Feel free to provide input in this ticket, it will be worked on here.\r\n\r\nMy only suggestion here would be for us to include some latency to the banners - i.e. if I go offline, we for an appropriate timeframe (e.g. 3-4 seconds) before reporting it to the user via the banner. We could also check the issue is still in place again just before presenting the banner and if it isn't we don't show it. That way we mitigate against over-communicating to the user and filling their screen with notifications. \r\n\r\nS, in summary, the suggestion would be:\r\n\r\n1) Detect issue (don't show notification banner immediately)\r\n2) Wait [n] seconds before showing notification banner (whatever period of time we feel appropriate)\r\n3) Just before showing the notification banner check again to ensure the issue is still valid / persistent\r\n4) Based on the outcome of 3 - show banner if issue persists, show nothing if issue has gone away \r\n\r\nThe only downside I see to this from a UX perspective (but perhaps preferable to being flashed lots of notification banners unnecessarily) is that if the issue does persist during the latency window, the app may appear unresponsive in some regards depending on the issue - but it would only be for a couple of seconds.\r\n\r\nWDYT @John-44 \r\n",
